","additionalTicketText":"General Admission","ageLimitCode":"OVER_21","ageLimit":"21 and Over","showTypeCode":null,"showType":"","eventStatusCode":"BUY","eventStatus":"Buy","eventStatusMessage":"","ticketPurchaseUrl":"https://www.ticketfly.com/purchase/event/1338533?utm_medium=api","ticketPrice":"$10.00","externalTicketingUrls":[],"multiEventCartable":true,"facebookEventId":"","facebookEventIdString":"","headliners":[{"id":1733489,"name":"Revel In Dimes","startTime":null,"eventDescription":"The destiny of Revel In Dimes, the blues-based rock & roll band with strokes of punk and soul, began 10 years ago when guitarist Eric Simons met drummer, Washington Duke as hired guns for recording sessions. They’d often invite one another on gigs or projects that either was working on, but found a common love and release in playing what Eric called “foot stomping and howling-to-the-moon blues.” And he would know growing up in Northeast Kansas, and spending much of his formative years as a musician in various bands touring throughout the midwest and deep south. While Eric knew this music well, making it the very fabric for his style of guitar playing, it was Washington’s roots in jazz that added a fresh swing to things. Studying everything from bebop to the blues under mentor Paul Jeffry and playing with the likes of Curtis Fuller, he was able to cut his teeth and really understand the infinite possibilities of rhythm and what he as a drummer could do with it. What the two couldn’t figure out was, if the blues had given them this visceral feeling, churned out such artistry, and spawned so many gold records, then why wasn’t anyone else playing it? The spark was lit. The two consulted the juke rhythms of Junior Kimbrough and R.L. Burnside and the electrified riffs of Charlie Patton among countless other blues legends and started a blues trio called ‘The Dukes.’ The concept was stripped down, gritty, North Mississippi style, swinging blues/rock & roll, and would later serve as the premise for Revel in Dimes. The Dukes played locally for a little over two years, but when their bassist departed Eric and Washington found themselves back as a duo. It was shortly thereafter that the two met Kia Warren, their future frontwoman. When Kia saw them play for the first time – two guys covering T. Model Ford at full volume on a Sunday at the Surf Lodge in Montauk – their live set stopped her dead in her tracks. There was a grittiness and honesty to their sound that her foray from Gospel into R&B hadn’t yet given her the opportunity to explore. She convinced them on the spot to let her join on vocals for a few tracks, and Revel In Dimes was born; but not complete. With a new lead singer in tow, it was obvious that a bass player would be needed to round out the lineup. Having lived in Brooklyn for years and playing for numerous bands and noteworthy artists (Babaloo, Navegante, Ladybug Mecca (Digable Planets), Washington sent feelers out in hopes of finding a talented, reliable, and not overly-committed bassist . Anyone who knows the New York music scene, knows that this would be a tall order. But what they found in Christopher “Premo” Waller would far surpass their expectations. As a fixture on the NYC punk scene, Premo had played guitar, drums and bass in multiple bands (Rebelmatic, OSM, Violent Sex), toured around the U.S. (including Afro Punk and Punk Island), and performed with Fishbones lead singer Angelo Moore and Bad Brains singer HR. This allowed him to deftly incorporate the influence of punk into the Revel in Dimes sound, while creating a groove for even the most frenetic songs. What comes next for this genre-bending band who have already taken the stage at SXSW, Art Basel, CMJ, and the Holland festival circuit?
